726232f-a.folder: Broadway & St. James Avenue, Queens, NY
726232f-a.text:
Broadway, at the N.E. corner of St. James Avenue, showing the parish house of St. James Protestant Episcopal Church, formerly for many years the rectory. The main building, according to Mr. Ogden, is about 100 years old. The two-story extension was added much later. Mr. Ogden also states that Mrs. Ogden, who was born in 1872, remembers the building before the extension was added. On the right can be seen part of the church --not the original one--at the corner of Corona Avenue. View 2
shows the rear of the house.
Gift of Beecher Ogden  1941
NO REPRODUCTIONS  Views 1,2

726234f-a.folder: Broadway & St. James Avenue, Queens, NY
726234f-a.text:
Proadway east side, at and adjoiiing St. James Avenue. At the extreme rimht, partially shown, is the St. James P.E. Parsonage. The building in the center of the view vas partly occupied by Dr. F. Boothe in 1875. Mrs. Palmer was the owner in 1873 and Dr. Coombs in 1891. The house at the left was the property of W.5. Wood in 1873, Dr. Poothe was born in Counecticut in 1876 and came to Newtown about 1875. He still resided here in 1896. All buildings between St. James Averue and the Long Island Railroad, Flushing, and North Side Division, on the east side of Broadwav,
were erected by Samuel Lord in 1850.

726235f-a.folder: Broadway & St. James Avenue, Queens, NY
726235f-a.text:
Broadway east side, north from St. James Avenue, to South Railroad Avenue, showing a group of houses erected by S. Lord in 1850. View No. 2 shows the rears of the same homes looking south from South Railroad Avenue. View No. 3 shows the only house left of the group in this view. It was known as Dr. Boothe's house and was located at the N.E. corner of the above first two mentioned streets.
1922
View 2: April 1925
View 3: Mav 1929.
Euoene L. Armbruster Collection

726237f-a.folder: Broadway & St. James Avenue, Queens, NY
726237f-a.text:
Broadway, east side, between South Railroad and St. James Avenues, showing several houses, built by S. Lord in 1873. Occupants of these dwellings in 1873, were (left to right) Dr. J. C. Wright,
Lr. G. P. Wright, and W. S. Wood.
View 2 shows the first house of the group, Dongan Avenue was
later cut through here.
VView 1:  Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  April, 1925
View 2:  P. L. Sperr  June 7, 1927
